JLPT N3/Day1

 I have broken down the material into four logical categories based on the sources.
1. Cause and Effect: Good vs. Bad Results
The most important distinction in these first two grammar points is whether the result is something you feel is positive or negative.
A おかげで B (Thanks to A, B): Use this when A causes a good result (B)
.
Rule: You cannot use this for bad results
.
Nuance: It can be used to express gratitude, such as 「おかげさまで」 (Thanks to you)
.
Example: Passing a test because a teacher taught you (先生に教えていただいたおかげで、合格することができました)
.
A せいで B (Because of A, B): Use this when A causes a bad result (B)
.
Rule: You cannot use this for good results. Whether a result is "good" or "bad" depends on your own perspective
.
Example: Having no appetite because of a fever (熱のせいで、食欲がない)
.
2. Formal and Neutral Cause and Effect
These points are often used in writing or more formal situations.
A 結果 B (As a result of A, B): This is a formal, written expression
.
Rule: Unlike the points above, the result can be either good or bad
.
Example: Improving listening skills after watching Japanese dramas every day (毎日30分日本のドラマを見続けた結果、聴解力が上がった)
.
A ため（に） B (Due to/Because of A, B): This is also a formal, written way to state a cause
.
Example: A train delay due to an accident (人身事故のため、一部の列車に遅れが出ています)
.
3. Expressing Extremes
These are used when a situation or emotion is so extreme that it causes a specific (usually negative or unusual) outcome.
あまりに（も） A: Use this when A is extreme or surpasses a normal level, leading to a bad result
.
Nuance: It is often used to express negative feelings or criticism
.
Example: It being so hot that you couldn't leave the house (あまりに暑くて、今日は家から一歩も出られなかった)
.
A あまり B: This focuses on an extreme emotion or state (A) causing an irregular or bad result (B)
.
Example: Crying out of extreme happiness (嬉しさのあまり泣き出した)
.
4. Expressing Purpose (Goal)
The sources show two ways to say "in order to," depending on the type of verb you use for your goal.
A ため（に） B (In order to A, do B): Used with volitional verbs (actions you control, like "to buy" or "to work")
.
Example: Studying Japanese in order to work in Japan (日本で働くために、日本語を勉強しています)
.
A ように B (In order to A, B): Used with non-volitional verbs (like "to understand"), or verbs in the potential (can do), negative (don't do), or passive forms
.
Example: Leaving early so you can be on time (約束の時間に間に合うように、早く家を出ようと思います)
.
Important General Rule
For almost all these grammar points (おかげで, せいで, 結果, あまり, ため (reason)), you cannot use volitional endings like ～たい (I want to) or ～てください (please do) at the very end of the sentence
